class lass , Whatĺs in that name? To me it brought back the sixties and those who swore to establish a classless society within our borders and used the same guerilla tactics I saw in nam duing their demonstrations at home.  A lot has to do with the time we served in Nam and where we served there. At first your defense of spatz barry deserved to be scrutinize if not exhortation by those of us who have had to deal with his deceitful ways. Your words;<br>
ôIf he has truly left, expect to be bored. Spatz was the guy everyone loved to hate. The sole voice in the wilderness of former protestors with enough balls to take on Vietnam vets no less. He'd open his mouth and firmly stick his foot in it on our turf. But he was willing to listen, wanted to understand, would consider, and would even capitulate when we jumped on him and explained the other side of the issue. Just because he was a protestor doesn't mean he was a coward. Just like every soldier wasn't a women and baby killer. There has been too much name calling. It isn't productive and it is probably a symptom of the Ptsd.ö <br><br>
Told me a lot, and my former response were according to those postings. <br>
If you had been there in Nam when and where I was it wouldnĺt have made a difference who you were or what you were doing there. <br>
The first time I saw a round eyes in Nam after eight months of slant eyed gooks was at An Hoa and they were German nurses and Catholic nuns that aided and supplied food and medication to the enemy but I could forgive them for that, not because of their humanitarian affections, but simply because they were round eyed women.  Just seeing them, brought me back to the realization that there was another world, a real world back in the states. If that was your only contribution in Nam, that would have been fine with me. Other then that, the only connection I had with Red cross workers in Nam was when they contacted my commanding officer on account my wife back home was complaining that I wasnĺt writing. Heck my world was the war, and she didnĺt want to hear that. When I wrote to her from the bush using toilet tissue which was the only paper we had, she really got upset and the Red cross once again had my Co get on my case. But they were doing their job and I forgave them for it.<br>
Forgive gooks and protestors, have no problem in forgiving gooks, I just killed them I didnĺt hate them. You donĺt need to hate the enemy in order to kill them. But protestors, well I donĺt hate them either, forgive them ask the Marines that died by my side and the many others that died and were wounded who never received proper honor in our country in service for our country on account of classless communist protestors and ignorant individuals that called them selves patriots but were responsible for igniting and fueling the hatred and demonstrations leveled at the returning Vietnam veterans. When those honorable servicemen that died, forgive the protestors so will I. But then, I may forgive but not forget. <br><br>

